**DFS Recusive Approach**
The reason why we update min and max at every step is because:
1. For every left node, the max value it can have it less than its parent's and the min value it can have is the left most node for that particular subtree.
2. For every right node, the max value it can have it less than the right most node of that particular subtree  and the min value it can have is the root value.

Time Complexity: O (n)
Space Complexity: O (n) (For the recursion Stack)
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isValidBSTHelper (TreeNode* currentNode, TreeNode* min, TreeNode* max) {
        if (currentNode==NULL) return true;               
        if (min && currentNode->val <= min->val) return false;
        if (max && currentNode->val >= max->val) return false;

        return isValidBSTHelper (currentNode->left, min, currentNode) && isValidBSTHelper (currentNode->right, currentNode, max);
    }

    bool isValidBST(TreeNode* root) {
        return isValidBSTHelper (root, NULL, NULL);
    }
};
```
This is a [nice intuitive solution](https://leetcode.com/problems/validate-binary-search-tree/discuss/990894/C%2B%2B-faster-than-90.55-of-C%2B%2B-and-less-than-87.48-of-C%2B%2B)

**Iterative Inorder Stack Solution**
Time Complexity: O(N)
Space Complexity: O(N)
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isValidBST(TreeNode* root) {
        stack <TreeNode*> s;        
        TreeNode* pre=NULL;

        while (root || !s.empty()) {
            while (root) {
                s.push(root);
                root=root->left;
            }
            root=s.top(), s.pop();

            if (pre!=NULL && root->val<=pre->val) return false;
            pre=root;
            root=root->right;
        }
        return true;
    }
};
```
Very nice article https://leetcode.com/problems/validate-binary-search-tree/discuss/32112/Learn-one-iterative-inorder-traversal-apply-it-to-multiple-tree-questions-(Java-Solution)

