# Approach
For this problem, we need to choose one biggest value > `Integer.MAX_VALUE`
and one smallest value < `Integer.MIN_VALUE` as the maximum and minimum, respectively. They could not be equal, otherwise cases like
```
root = [2147483647]
root = [2147483647, 2147483647]
```
will be failed.

`Long.MAX_VALUE` and `Long.MIN_VALUE` are luckily the two that meet our needs. However, if unluckily in the future the LeetCode admin adds them into the test cases, cases like
```
root = [9223372036854775807]
root = [9223372036854775807, 9223372036854775807]
```
will be failed again.

Therefore, it is better to avoid using them. We can simply replace the `int` or `long` with `TreeNode`, and set them to `null` when calling the helper function, as shown in the code below.

# Reference
https://algs4.cs.princeton.edu/32bst/BST.java.html

# Code
```
/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * public class TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode left;
 *     TreeNode right;
 *     TreeNode() {}
 *     TreeNode(int val) { this.val = val; }
 *     TreeNode(int val, TreeNode left, TreeNode right) {
 *         this.val = val;
 *         this.left = left;
 *         this.right = right;
 *     }
 * }
 */
class Solution {
    public boolean isValidBST(TreeNode root) {
        return isValidBST(root, null, null);
    }

    private boolean isValidBST(TreeNode root, TreeNode min, TreeNode max) {
        if (root == null) {
            return true;
        }

        if (min != null && root.val <= min.val) {
            return false;
        }

        if (max != null && root.val >= max.val) {
            return false;
        }
        return isValidBST(root.left, min, root) 
                && isValidBST(root.right, root, max);
    }
}
```

