# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
If you clearly understand the question, it states that you just need to check whether the BST is valid or not, and when we traverse a BST using INORDER, the output stream will be a sorted list.

# Simple Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We can traverse the BST using Inorder and store each output element in a list, and check whether the list is sorted or not.

**FOR EXAMPLE:**
If the BST looks something like this:
![djanj.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/4435e6a0-5248-45a0-97bf-a83d668f8569_1677843929.3729975.png)

The **INORDER** traversal will be - [1, 3, 4, 6, 7, 8, 10, 13, 14]
And if a tree is a BST the inorder will be sorted;

The above tree is a valid BST, and we can check that using the above inorder list.


# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N) for traversing tree and O(N) for checking if resultant list is sorted or not,  N = Number of Nodes in a tree.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(N) in worst case if tree is skewed, and O(N) space for storing each element in a list.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * struct TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode *left;
 *     TreeNode *right;
 *     TreeNode() : val(0), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}
 *     TreeNode(int x) : val(x), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}
 *     TreeNode(int x, TreeNode *left, TreeNode *right) : val(x), left(left), right(right) {}
 * };
 */
class Solution {
public:

    // Travserse entire tree using inorder, and store each element inside the res.
    void inorder(TreeNode* root, vector<int>&res) {
        if(!root) return;
        inorder(root->left, res);
        res.push_back(root->val);
        inorder(root->right, res);
    }

    bool isValidBST(TreeNode* root) {
        vector<int> res;
        inorder(root, res);
        for(int i=1; i<res.size(); ++i) {
            // Checking if res[i-1] >= res[i] then return false;
            // That means the input tree is not a valid BST;
            if(res[i-1]>=res[i]) return false;
        }
        return true;
        // Follow up: solve this without using any extra space.
        // Hint: You can use ranges, for each element.
    }
};

```

