In interview, it's possible to be asked to implement this question in all of three tree traversal methods. If you like my solution, please upvote!

Preorder maintains a interval in the search function
```
class Solution {
    public boolean isValidBST(TreeNode root) {
        return helper(root, Long.MIN_VALUE, Long.MAX_VALUE);
    }

    private boolean helper(TreeNode root, long lo, long hi) {
        if (root == null) return true;
        if (root.val >= hi || root.val <= lo) return false;
        return helper(root.left, lo, root.val) && helper(root.right, root.val, hi);
    }
}
```

Inorder maintains a previous node to compare with the current node
```
class Solution {
    private TreeNode prev;

    public boolean isValidBST(TreeNode root) {
        return helper(root);
    }

    private boolean helper(TreeNode root) {
        if (root == null) return true;
        if (!helper(root.left)) return false;
        if (prev != null && prev.val >= root.val) return false;
        prev = root;
        return helper(root.right);
    }
}
```

Postorder should return a interval which represents the lower and upper bound of the subtree
```
class Solution {
    private boolean ans;

    public boolean isValidBST(TreeNode root) {
        ans = true;
        postorder(root);
        return ans;
    }

    private int[] postorder(TreeNode root) {
        if (root == null) return null;
        int[] left = postorder(root.left);
        int[] right = postorder(root.right);
        if (left != null && left[1] >= root.val) ans = false;
        if (right != null && right[0] <= root.val) ans = false; 
        int[] tmp = new int[2];
        tmp[0] = left == null ? root.val : left[0];
        tmp[1] = right == null ? root.val : right[1];
        return tmp;
    }
}
```

