solutions.content:
The best way to start DP related problem is to think about the problem first and build a recursive strategy. This is because recursion is easier and you can apply memoization rather quickly compared to tabulation. And you will get a solution anyway after which you can optimize the solution. In any interview, getting a solution is the key.

Let's take the sample here:

```
[ 2, 7, 9, 3, 1 ]
```

Let's say we start at house with amount 2. Then we can do two things:

- Skip the house and move on
- Rob the house and skip next house

We can make this generic by saying at any starting house. And we want to start at the very first house (only start the logic, to rob or not is a different thing) since we want to maximize the robbery. So Let's turn this into the most naive recursive solution.

```javascript
// O(2^n) time | O(2^n) space
var rob = function(nums, idx = 0) {
    if (idx >= nums.length) {
        return 0;
    }

    const sumIfSkipped = rob(nums, idx + 1);
    const sumIfRobbed = nums[idx] + rob(nums, idx + 2);

    return Math.max(sumIfSkipped, sumIfRobbed);
};
```

You know what happened when I submit this solution? You guessed it right, it timed out. The reason is, we are doing the same work multiple times, at each index. To speed it up, let's add memoization to it.

```javascript
// O(n) time | O(n) space
var rob = function(nums, idx = 0, memo = {}) {
    if (idx in memo) {
        return memo[idx];
    }

    if (idx >= nums.length) {
        return 0;
    }

    const sumIfSkipped = rob(nums, idx + 1, memo);
    const sumIfRobbed = nums[idx] + rob(nums, idx + 2, memo);

    return memo[idx] = Math.max(sumIfSkipped, sumIfRobbed);
};
```

This is better, from exponential (2 to the power of n) to 2 times n in complexity. The results of my run are as follows:

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/c469eb53-70b2-49ec-8122-3b47e9f85bb1_1632851070.6599624.png)

It was fast, but I think we can certainly do better. And that is by using iteration instead of recursion. We start by observing the existing code, and we make two observations:

- If we decide to skip the house at index i, then we are computing max robbery possible starting from house at index i+1.
- If we decide to rob the house at index i, then we are computing max robbery possible starting from house at index i+2.

So at every house, we are doing two lookups. To make this easier, let's construct a DP table and iterate the given array from right to left. This is why tabulation is also called as bottom-up approach.

```javascript
// O(n) time | O(n) space
var rob = function(nums) {
    const table = new Array(nums.length + 2);

    table[nums.length + 0] = 0;
    table[nums.length + 1] = 0;

    for (let i = nums.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        const sumIfSkipped = table[i + 1];
        const sumIfRobbed = nums[i] + table[i + 2];

        table[i] = Math.max(sumIfSkipped, sumIfRobbed);
    }

    return table[0];
}
```

The complexity is the same as the previous solution with memoization, but this is even faster, since we are skipping the stack frames and recursive function calls. The results of my run are as follows:

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/f0849698-cb8a-4204-8e69-dbe196864630_1632851628.583106.png)

We aren't done yet! If you notice, we are only making two lookups, and we can reduce the space complexity if we get rid of the table and use two variables for that. This way, we will get the solution to O(1) space, which will super impress your interviewer.

```javascript
// O(n) time | O(1) space
var rob = function(nums) {
    let robbedIdxPlus1 = 0;
    let robbedIdxPlus2 = 0;

    for (let i = nums.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        const sumIfSkipped = robbedIdxPlus1;
        const sumIfRobbed = nums[i] + robbedIdxPlus2;

        const maxRobbedAtIdx = Math.max(sumIfSkipped, sumIfRobbed);

        robbedIdxPlus2 = robbedIdxPlus1;
        robbedIdxPlus1 = maxRobbedAtIdx;
    }

    return robbedIdxPlus1;
}
```

And the results? Here is an even faster submission:

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/32293b77-c7ce-47c3-862b-fe738c069134_1632851778.8733077.png)

Are we done? I think so. If you find an even better way, be sure to let me know in the comments!

