I will go through step by step to get you understand in better way, so that you all can solve further dp problems easily. *( for being beginner in solving dp problems i can understand the pain,but believe me after this solution you all will get some idea that how to tackle dp problem )*. :)

okay, we will start with basics :
**Ques**  what if only one house was there?
**Ans** So easy right :D , thief will rob that house and get the money.

**Ques** what if two house were there with different amount of money?
**Ans** umm,not that difficult, the one with max amount of money, thief will go into that house. Easy right !

Real problem comes when we have more number of house, but believe me you have already cracked the logic.

So, assume you are starting with first house, after that you can either go to third or fourth or fifth or sixth or last one, depending on which house will give you more profit.(robber can't go to second house as it is adjacent to first).
right? That makes sense !
But out of that third or fourth or fifth or sixth etc.. which house to choose?
**Ans** Here comes the idea of storing value into an array and that array will going to store maximum amount of money robber can get, if he chooses any house as first house to rob.
ex : let us suppose 7 houses are there with some amount of money correspondingly :

h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6,h7.
23,12,32,26,20,21,19.

Assume robber can go from left to right only,
so if he start with h6 or h7  leaving behind all the houses,maximum amount of money he will get same as amount is present in h6 or h7, (as we are assuming robber can go only  left to right).

we will make array as same size of amount array,and name as **dp[ ] =** __ , __ , __ , __ , __ , 21 , 19 (assume index starting from 1 and index representing house numbers).
here each index will going to store maximum amount of money robber will get, if he start robing from that particular house.
you can see that h6 and h7 house values are directly written in dp array.

okay,let us come to analysis :
if robber went to h1, then next house which he has to go depends on which house is giving maximum amount of money out of h3,h4,h5,h6,h7.

STEP 1 : **max amount of money if he start from h1 or dp[1]= amount of money he get from h1 house + Max amount of money from (h3,h4,h5,h6,h7).**
okay,but how we will going to calculate max amount robber can get from h3,h4,h5,h6,h7.
**Ans** Same as above !
STEP 2 :**max amount of money if he start from h3 or dp[3] = amount of money he get from h3 house + Max amount of money from (h5,h6,h7).**
like wise we will continue in recursive fashion,until we hit the second last house or last house.

STEP 3 : **max amount of money if he start from h5 or dp[5]= amount of money he get from h5 house + Max amount of money from (h7).**
**dp[5]=20+19**
**dp[ ] =** __ , __ , __ , __ , 39 , 21 , 19. 
now we can calculate for *STEP 2* ,
dp[3]=amount in house h3 + max amount we can get from (h5,h6,h7).
dp[3]=32 + max of (39,21,19).
dp[3]=71
**dp[ ] =** __ , __ , 71 , __ , 39 , 21 , 19.
now we can calculate same for *STEP 1*,
dp[1]=amount in house h1 + max amount we can get from (h3,h4,h5,h6,h7).
But,
we know what max amount we can get from h3,h5,h6,h7 but don't know about h4.At first, we need to calculate that :
STEP 4 : **max amount of money if he start from h4 or dp[4] = amount of money he get from h4 house + Max amount of money from (h6,h7)**
dp[4]=26+ max of (21,19)
dp[4]=47
**dp[ ] =** __ , __ , 71 , 47 , 39 , 21 , 19.
now, we can go back to calculate *STEP 1* 
dp[1]=amount in house h1 + max amount we can get from (h3,h4,h5,h6,h7).
dp[1]=23+max of (71,47,39,21,19)
dp[1]=94
**dp[ ] =** 94, __ , 71 , 47 , 39 , 21 , 19.
STEP 5 : **max amount of money if he start from h2or dp[2] = amount of money he get from h4 house + Max amount of money from (h4,h5,h6,h7)**
dp[2]=12+ max of(47,39,21,19)
dp[2]=59
**dp[ ] =** 94, 59 , 71 , 47 , 39 , 21 , 19.
since in question asking for the maximum amount, so the answer is 94.

