This is very simple 1-D DP problem. At every position we have two choices, either we can choose current house and add it with the previous alternate i.e 
```
dp[i] = nums[i] + dp[i - 2];
```
or we can select the previous for maximum answer
```
dp[i] = dp[i -1]
```
So now we merge them 
```
dp[i] = max(dp[i - 1], dp[i - 2] + nums[i])
```
This approach is used in many similar problems in which we have to select alternates.

## Lets code it:

```
class Solution {
    int dp[105];
public:
    int rob(vector<int>& nums) {
        int n = nums.size();

        if(n == 0) return 0;        
        dp[0] = nums[0];        

        if(n == 1) return dp[0];        		
        dp[1] = max(dp[0], nums[1]);        

        for(int i = 2; i < n; i++){
            dp[i] = max(dp[i - 1], dp[i - 2] + nums[i]);
        }
        return dp[n - 1];
    }
};
```
**TC : O(n)
Space : O(n)**

## Further Space Optimization
As we can see we need to maintain 3 states
1. dp[i - 2] - previous answer -> ```prev1```
2. dp[i - 1] - previous alternate answer -> ```prev2```
3. dp[i] - current answer -> ```ans```

So we will replace dp array with above 3 variables

```
class Solution {
public:
    int rob(vector<int>& nums) {
        int n = nums.size();
        if(n == 0) return 0;

        int prev1, prev2;
        prev1 = nums[0];

        if(n == 1) return prev1;

        prev2 = max(prev1, nums[1]);
        int ans = prev2;
        for(int i = 2; i < n; i++){
            ans = max(prev2, prev1 + nums[i]);
            prev1 = prev2;
            prev2 = ans;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```
**TC : O(n)
Space : O(1)**

