solutions.content:
**Please upvote if you like the solution and feel free to comment if you have any query**

**APPROACH:**
Let ans[i] be the maximum amount of money the robber can steal till the ith house.

Suppose the robber is at house i, so he has 2 choices:
* Rob the current house. After this he cannot rob the house no i-1 due to the adjacent constraints given in the problem so we move on to finding the answer till house no i-2.
* Skip the current house and find the answer till the house no i-1.

So the relation becomes **ans[i]=max(ans[i-1],nums[i]+ans[i-2])**

The base case will arise when:
1. i=0: In this case we have only 1 house so we rob money from it and the answer for this subproblem will be nums[0]
2. i=1. In this case we have 2 houses so we can either steal from second house and skip the first or skip the second and steal from first. so the answer for this subproblem will be max(nums[0],nums[1])

For other cases, we use the relation defined earlier in this explanation.

Using this relation one can use a dp array to store the answer till the ith and (i-1)th index and use then to calculate the answer till (i+1)th index. But this solution will have a O(N) space complexity. 

We can definitely improve it. Have a close look at the relation and you'll observe that we're using the anwsers of the previous 2 indexes only so we can store them into 2 variables and update them accordingly when a new iteration begins.

So we finally have a solution with O(N) time complexity and O(1)  space complexity.

**CODE**

```
class Solution {
public:
    int rob(vector<int>& nums) {
        int n=nums.size();
        if(n==1)
            return nums[0];
        int a=nums[0],b=max(nums[0],nums[1]);
        for(int i=2;i<n;i++){
            int tmp=b;
            b=max(nums[i]+a,b);
            a=tmp;
        }
        return b;
    }
};
```
