solutions.content:
**Logic :** 
* If you observe carefully, then you can see that this is a decision making problem as on each step we have the choice of taking it (robbing that house) or not take it (not robbing that house). 

* If we take it then we add it to our sum and skip 1 house to move to the third one.. If we don't take it then we move to the next house and don't add anything to our sum/or add 0.

* At every step, we calculate the maximum out of both the situations and move forward accordingly.

**Approach 1 : Normal Recursion**

```
       int solve(int i, vector<int>&nums){

        if(i==0){
            return nums[i];
        }    
        if(i<0){                         // prevents negative indexing for take case
            return 0;
        }

        int take = solve(i-2,nums)+nums[i];     //adding nums[i] and skipping 1 house
        int not_take = solve(i-1,nums)+0;       //adding 0 and moving to the next house

        return max(take,not_take);              // return max of both situations
    }

    int rob(vector<int>& nums) {
         return solve(nums.size()-1,nums);
    }
```

Time : O(2^N)   
Space : O(N)     --> Recursion stack space


**Approach 2 : Recursion -> Memoization**

* We can see that there are many subproblems that are computed already and now are being recomputed like for f(5) we need f(4) and f(3) and then for f(4) we again need f(3) and f(2). So it is evident that we are recalculating a lot of stuff.

* So, we are going to memoize it using a dp vector where we store the values which we calculate during recursion. If the value is stored in dp vector we will use it directly and won't recalculate the same thing again, otherwise we will solve that subproblem and store its value in dp vector.

```
       int solve(int i, vector<int>&nums,vector<int>&dp){

        if(i==0){
            return nums[i];
        }    
        if(i<0){
            return 0;
        }        

        if(dp[i]!=-1){           // if value is precalculated then use it
            return dp[i];
        }

        int take = solve(i-2,nums,dp)+nums[i];  // else calculate it 
        int not_take = solve(i-1,nums,dp)+0;

        dp[i]=max(take,not_take);              // after calculation store it in dp vector to reuse it and prevent recalculation.
        return dp[i];
    }

    int rob(vector<int>& nums) {
        vector<int>dp(nums.size()+1,-1);
        return solve(nums.size()-1,nums,dp);
    }
```

Space : O(N) for recursion and O(N) for Dp vector
Time : O(N)

**Approach 3 : Tabulation**

* We can see that we are taking an extra O(N) space for recursion. Let's remove it by converting our top-down approach to an iterative bottom-up approach.

```
        int rob(vector<int>& nums) {
        vector<int>dp(nums.size(),-1);

        dp[0]=nums[0];

        for(int i = 1;i<nums.size();i++){
            if(i>1) dp[i] = max(dp[i-1],dp[i-2]+nums[i]); // taking the max of take and non take conditions
            else dp[i] = max(dp[i-1],nums[i]);      //bcs if i=1 , dp[i-2] won't exist
        }
        return dp[nums.size()-1];
    }
```

Time : O(N)
Space : O(N)

**Approach 4 : Space optimized to O(1)**

* If you observe the solution of approach 3 carefully, you will notice that at each step we require only dp[i-1] and dp[i-2] i.e. the previous 2 values of function.

* We don't need to maintain the whole dp vector .. we can just keep track of the last two values of the function to obtain the current value and keep modifying our three pointers.

```
        int rob(vector<int>& nums) {
        vector<int>dp(nums.size(),-1);

        int prev = nums[0];
        int curr,prev2;

        for(int i = 1;i<nums.size();i++){

           if(i>1) curr = max(prev,prev2+nums[i]);
            else curr = max(prev,nums[i]);
            prev2 = prev;
            prev = curr;   
        }
        return prev;
    }
```

Space : O(1)
Time : O(N)

