# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We solve the following subproblem: What is the optimal sum we can get up to some index?

This is trivial for the first element.
After that we take the maximum of either the value plus its second last element or just the last element.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We save the maxima for the last and second last elements and iterate over the array.


# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$ - We iterate once over the whole array.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->


- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$ - We only save the results of the last two iterations.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
typedef int32_t i32;


inline i32
maximum(i32 x, i32 y)
{
    return x > y ? x : y;
}


i32
rob(i32 *numbers, size_t numbersLength)
{
    i32 prePredecessor  = 0;
    i32 predecessor     = 0;
    i32 current         = 0;

    for (size_t index = 0; index < numbersLength; index += 1)
    {
        prePredecessor  = predecessor;
        predecessor     = current;
        current         = maximum(prePredecessor + numbers[index], predecessor);
    }

    return current;
}
```

