solutions.content:
**Solution 1: Using Map**
Creating a map of nums containing an array of indexes in which a num is present. Then using Math.Random() function, getting an index from among the array of indices.
```
class Solution {
    constructor(nums) {
        this.nums = nums;
        this.map = this.createMap();    // O(n)
    }
    createMap() {   // O(n)
        const map = new Map();
        this.nums.forEach((num, idx) => {
            const numIdxs = map.has(num) ? map.get(num) : [];
            numIdxs.push(idx);
            map.set(num, numIdxs);
        })
        return map;
    }
    pick(target) {  // O(1)
        const targetIdxOptions = this.map.get(target);
        const randomIdx = Math.floor(Math.random() * targetIdxOptions.length);
        return targetIdxOptions[randomIdx];
    }
}
```
Time Complexity = 
`Initialization = O(n)`
`Pick - O(1)`
Space Complexity = O(n)

----

**Solution 2: Reservoir Sampling**
This approach optimises on Space from O(n) to O(1).

```
class Solution {
    constructor(nums) {
        this.nums = nums;
    }
    pick(target) {  // O(n)
        let count = 0;
        let picked = 0;

        this.nums.forEach((num, idx) => {
            if(num === target) {
                ++count;
                const probOfPicked = Math.floor(Math.random() * count);

				// probOfPicked value can be an int within the range [0, count)
				// so probability of it being (count - 1) is 1/count
				// since we have to chose each index uniformly in a random fashion
                if(probOfPicked === (count - 1)) {
                    picked = idx;
                }
            }
        })
        return picked;
    }
}
```
Time Complexity = 
`Initialization = O(1)`
`Pick - O(n)`
Space Complexity = O(1)

In this solution, we do not need to pre-process and create a map. That is, there is no need to have a buffer with indices of the possible target value.
If we consider input as a stream - for an unlimited stream, we cannot have an unlimited space. Then this solution works very well.

