solutions.content:
# Approach 1
This is the simplest of the two approaches :
**`On careful observation we can see that on any diagonal the sum of indices for all the elements is same`**. Make a map with the key as the sum of indices and store a vector corresponding to the key value.
`Ordered map` shall be used as we need to store the keys in a sorted order.
Also if we observe carefully we can see that for upward diagonal the upper element would be stored first, so for that we will need to traverse the vector from the end.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(N*N Log(N))

- Space complexity:
O(N)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> findDiagonalOrder(vector<vector<int>>& mat) {
        int row = mat.size();
        int col = mat[0].size();
        vector <int> ans;
        map <int,vector<int>> mp;

        for( int i = 0; i < row; i++ ){
            for( int j = 0; j < col; j++ ){
                mp[i+j].push_back(mat[i][j]);
            }
        }

        for( auto it : mp ){
            if( it.first % 2 == 0 ){
                for(int j = it.second.size() - 1; j >= 0; j-- ){
                    ans.push_back(it.second[j]);
                }
            }
            else{
                for( int j = 0; j < it.second.size(); j++ ){
                    ans.push_back(it.second[j]);
                }
            }
        }

        return ans;

    }
};
```
# Approach 2
Set up a boolean variable to check whether you need to go up or down.
Here you will need to take care of exiting the matrix. Let's talk about while we are going up :
1) We could have reached the c + 1 column
2) We could have reached -1st row.

In the first case we need to increase the rows by 2 and decrease the column by 1.
In the second case only the row need to be incremented by 1.
In either case set boolean to false to go in the opposite direction next.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(N*N)

- Space complexity:
O(N)
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> findDiagonalOrder(vector<vector<int>>& mat) {
        bool up = true;
        int row = mat.size(), col = mat[0].size();
        int r = 0, c = 0;
        vector<int> ans;
        while( r < row && c < col ){

            if( up ){
                ans.push_back(mat[r][c]);
                c += 1;
                r -= 1;
                if( (c == col) ){
                    r += 2;
                    c -= 1;
                    up = false;
                }
                else if( r < 0 ){
                    r += 1;
                    up = false;
