# Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(N*M)$$

- Space complexity:
$$O(N*M)$$

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    /*
        This solution leverages the fact that all the elements on
        a diagonal have a constant sum of their coordinates (x, y)
    */ 
    vector<int> findDiagonalOrder(vector<vector<int>>& mat) {
        int N = mat.size(); // number of lines of the matrix
        int M = mat[0].size(); // number of columns of the matrix
        vector<int> answer; // solution vector

        // x will be our line coordinate. To move upwards or downwards
        // the diagonal we will simply increment/decrement x respectively.
        int x = 0; 
        // sum will be used to identify the diagonal we are currently
        // working on. at any point in time we can determine the 
        // current column coordinate by subtracting x from sum. To
        // move on the next diagonal we can simply increment sum.
        int sum = 0; 
        // dir will indicate the moving direction on the current diagonal
        // when we move upwards the diagonal dir == -1, when we move
        // downwards the diagonal dir == 1. This will simplify the code later.
        int dir = -1;

        // add will add mat[x][y] to the answer
        // this should be called everytime we change coordinates
        auto addToAnswer = [&]() {
            int y = sum - x;
            answer.push_back(mat[x][y]);
        };

        // ok will check if a given x coordinate (y coordinate is determined
        // by sum - x) is within the matrix boundaries
        auto ok = [&](int x) {
            int y = sum - x;
            return x >= 0 && y >= 0 && x < N && y < M;
        };

        addToAnswer();

        // last diagonal will always consist of a single element,
        // specifically matrix[N - 1][M - 1]
        while (sum != N + M - 2) {
            // to move to the next diagonal we increment sum.
            // When we increment sum, y coordinate is incremented
            // automatically! This is good when we want to move to the
            // next diagonal by going to the right cell when we reach the 
            // end of the current diagonal, but this won't be always the case,
            // as sometimes we will need to move to the cell below to switch to 
            // the next diagonal
            sum++;

            // When we reached the end of a diagonal by moving upwards
            // we have two cases:
            // 1. If we did not reach yet the rightmost column, we will move to the right cell.
            //    This means we do not have to change x (we incremented sum and y coordinate was
            //    incremented subsequently)
            // 2. If we did reach the rightmost column, our only option is to move cell below, which
            //    means we should increment x

            // When we reached the end of a diagonal by moving downwards
            // we have two cases:
            // 1. If we did not reach yet the downmost line, we will move to the cell below.
            //    This means we have to increment x
            // 2. If we did reach the downmost line, our only option is to move right cell,
            //    this means we should not modify x

            // TLDR: We should increment x (move to the cell below) only when we hit
            //       rightmost column at the end of a diagonal by moving upwards, or when
            //       we did not hit yet the lowest line at the end of a diagonal by moving downwards.
            if ((dir == -1 && !ok(x)) || (dir == 1 && (ok(x + 1)))) {
                x++;
            }
            addToAnswer();


            // we swap direction
            dir = -dir;

            // we consume the current diagonal
            // as long as the coordinates determined by moving upwards/downwards
            // on the diagonal are within matrix boundaries
            // it's important to note that we only change x coordinate, as y is 
            // determined by sum and x
            while (ok(x + dir)) {
                x += dir;
                addToAnswer();
            }
        }

        return answer;   
    }
};
```

