I have solved the Diagonal Traverse using some basic algebraic geometry. The initial idea was to assume that diagonal is a line on the 2D plane. We can represent that line as y = -x + b. Where b is our diagonal index. From that point we have to provide extra conditions for range of x and range of b. 
The b range is simple [0, yMax + xMax -1]. 
The x range can be represented as [minX , maxX] where minX can be calculated from y = -x + b assuming that the y has to be between [0, yMax]. In that case
0 <= -x + b <= yMax
-b <= -x <= yMax  - b
b >= x >= b - yMax
Our second restriction on the x range is [0, maxX] If we combine them together we can represent it in java as: 
minX = Math.max(0, b - yMax)
maxX = Math.min(b, xMax)

The other requirement is to to change the direction of traversal with every new value of b. 
int dir = 1; // 1  up, -1 down
dir = -dir;


That will affect our initial value of x so
int x = dir == 1 ? minX : maxX; 

The interactive demo [Matrix Traversal Animation](https://www.desmos.com/calculator/pr8ttpqcl0)
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/01eced8c-4323-4824-b439-953f6a25d7f1_1593899064.1739016.png)


The full working algorithm with time complexity O(yMax * xMax) and space complexity O(1) assuming that the additional result array is the requirement of the task:

```
class Solution {
    public int[] findDiagonalOrder(int[][] matrix) {
        int yMax = matrix.length;
        int xMax = matrix[0].length;
        if (yMax == 0) {
            return new int[0];
        }
        int [] result = new int[xMax * yMax];
        int pos = 0;
        int dir = 1;

        for (int b = 0; b < xMax + yMax - 1; b++) {
            int minX = Math.max(b - (yMax - 1), 0);
            int maxX = Math.min(b, xMax - 1);
            int x = dir == 1 ? minX : maxX;

            while(x >= minX && x <= maxX) {
                int y = -x + b;
                result[pos++] = matrix[y][x];
                x += dir;
            }
            dir = -dir;
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```

