# Intuition
The problem is depicts what needs to be done. We have to traverse the matrix's diagonals alternately which is shown in the image provided.
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/0164a920-ed10-47c6-932a-acd8cdd5e7f2_1685994705.035149.png)
We have to move in this sort of zigzag fashion. There's nothing more to the intuition since we know that we have to simulate, so in this kind of question the approach is more important.


# Approach
We start from `(0,0)` and try moving towards the **top right**. Since we're at the top, we move to the next columns and change the direction to **bottom left**. We keep moving until we hit the left end. Here we have to move to the next row and **swap the direction** again. We keep repeating this until we reach the last element.

We have 4 condition to check (order matters):
We swap the directions in all 4 cases because they mean that we've reached an edge or a corner.
1. if `i==0` && `dirY == -1`. In this case we've reached a top most point from where we need to check if `j==n-1` because in that case we cannot increase `j` and have to increase `i` instead. This is because if we're at the last column, we need to go down because we clearly can't go right.
2. if `i==m-1` and `dirY == 1` then it means we've reached the last row. In this case we need to increase `j` by one so that we go to the next column to move to **top right** again.
3. if `j==0` and `dirX==-1`. If we've reached the first column, if we're at the first row we'll increase `j` otherwise we'll increase `i`. We've kept this condition after *2* because in case if we hit the bottom left corner, this operation will move the position out of the matrix's bounds.
4. if `j==n-1` and `dirX==1`. This condition occurs when we've reahed the last column. So we just increase `i` and go for the next diagonal.

In any other case we just move the current location based on our current direction.
Every iteration we add the current element to the result array,

# Code
```cpp []
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> findDiagonalOrder(vector<vector<int>>& mat) {
        int m = mat.size(), n=mat[0].size();
        int i{0}, j{0};
        vector<int> res;
        int dirY = -1, dirX = 1;
        while(i!=m-1 || j!=n-1) {
            res.push_back(mat[i][j]);
            if (i==0 && dirY==-1) {
                if (j==n-1)
                    i++;
                else
                    j++;
                swap(dirX, dirY);
            }
            else if (i==m-1 && dirY==1) {
                j++;
                swap(dirX, dirY);
            }
            else if (j==0 && dirX==-1) {
                if (i==0)
                    j++;
                else
                    i++;
                swap(dirX, dirY);
            }
            else if (j==n-1 && dirX==1) {
                i++;
                swap(dirX, dirY);
            }
            else {
                i += dirY;
                j += dirX;
            }
        }
        res.push_back(mat[i][j]);

        return res;
    }
};
```

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n*m)$$
Since we're traversing the entire matrix (just in a peculiar way).

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$
We're not using any extra space apart from storing the result which takes $$O(n*m)$$ space.


