solutions.content:
We need to figure out an approach to:
1. Maintain and change the direction of movement.
2. Finding the starting point after changing direction (head).

While going up from down, if the down diagonal ends in the last row, the head would be the element next to its tail. Otherwise, the head would be the directly below the tail of the down diagonal.

While going down from up, if the up diagonal ends in the last column, the head would be the element directly below its tail. Otherwise, the head would be to the right of the tail of the down diagonal.

Keeping the above cases in mind, the code follows:
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> findDiagonalOrder(vector<vector<int>>& matrix) {
        int rows = matrix.size(), cols = matrix[0].size(), i = 0, j = 0;        
        bool dir = true; //true for upwards right, false for downwards left
        vector<int> res(rows*cols);
        res[0] = matrix[i][j];
        int k = 1; //counter variable for result matrix
        while(i != rows - 1 || j != cols - 1){
            if(dir){ //if upwards right motion 
                if(j == cols - 1){ 
                    i++; dir = false;
                }
                else if(i == 0){
                    j++; dir = false;
                }
                else{ 
                    i--; j++; //to go upwards right if direction change not needed yet
                }
            }
            else{ //if downwards left motion
                if(i == rows - 1){ 
                    j++; dir = true;
                }
                else if(j == 0) { 
                    i++; dir = true;
                }
                else { 
                    i++; j--; //to go downwards right if direction change not needed yet
                }
            }
            res[k++] = matrix[i][j]; //adding the element to our result vector
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

