solutions.content:
**Approach**: since every iteration will add 1 to all elements in the submatrix that goes from [1,1] to [x,y] (using 1-index), we want to know the minimum x and y in array *ops*, because its area will have the greatest numbers (in particular, with value k, being k the number of iterations/length of *ops*).

First reduce searches for those minimum values.
Second reduce just multipiles them.

If there's no values in array *ops* then one should return the size of the whole matrix, so that's why the first reduce has [m,n] as its initial value.

# Code
```
/**
 * @param {number} m
 * @param {number} n
 * @param {number[][]} ops
 * @return {number}
 */
var maxCount = function(m, n, ops) {
    return ops.reduce((r,x) => [Math.min(x[0],r[0]), Math.min(x[1],r[1])], [m,n]).reduce((r,x) => r*x, 1);
};
```

