# Approach
Step 1. Sort ops.
Example of Sorted ops:
2 , 3 
2 , 1 
4 , 2 
7 , 4

Step 2. Iterate ops and find smallest row ops value (i) here it is 2 which is ops[0][0] always and find smallest coloumn ops value (j) here it is 1 which we can find in one iteration. 


Step 3. Now our max Integer will be i*j.

NOTE: If ops size is 0 simply return rows_size * coloumn_size i.e. m * n.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(NLogN)

- Space complexity:
O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maxCount(int m, int n, vector<vector<int>>& ops) {

        int maxIntegers=0;

        if(ops.size()>0){
            sort(ops.begin(), ops.end());
            int j=ops[0][1];

            for(int i=0; i<ops.size()-1; i++){
                if(j>ops[i+1][1]) j=ops[i+1][1];
                if(ops[i+1][1]==1) break;
            }
            int maxIntegers = ops[0][0]*j;
            return maxIntegers;
        }

        return m*n;

    }
};
```

